	   <a name=103883222549518></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f103883222549518><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=item.html?item=17200&mid=103883222549518>RE: dual weild use ?</a> <a id=fs8 href=item.html?item=17200&mid=103883222549518#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=48619><span id= >Kshaaz</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>1 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Dec 2nd 7:53 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>No, that's wrong.<br>Your offhand is completely unrelated to your primary hand. Each hand handles the delay itself.<br>When you start combat each hand has the chance to hit, the primary hand gets a double attack check and the offhand first has to pass the dual wield check and then a double attack check. After the delay of the primary hand it hits again depending on the skill checks. Otoh after the delay of the OFFHAND it gets a new dual wield check and then another double attack skill.<br><br>So, not your primary gets a dual wield check if the offhand gets a hit but the offhand gets the dual wield check after the delay of the offhand.<br><br>Hope this helps<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
